 We’ve all been in that meeting. The one where the manager stands in front of a whiteboard covered in sticky notes, eyes wide with excitement.
&ldquo;Okay team. These are all top priority tasks!&rdquo;
You scan the board. &ldquo;Urgent.&rdquo; &ldquo;Critical.&rdquo; &ldquo;Do Now.&rdquo; &ldquo;Top Priority.&rdquo;
Every single item is flagged as essential. Every feature is a must-have. Every bug is a showstopper.
When you ask the logical question: &ldquo;If they are all priority one, which one do we do first?&rdquo;. You get the classic answer:
&ldquo;Simple: just multitask everything.&rdquo;
It’s the great paradox of project management. Prioritization is supposed to be about choosing what not to do right now. But sometimes, it feels like the strategy is just &ldquo;do everything, immediately.&rdquo;
As the saying goes: When everything is a priority&hellip; nothing is. 😅

