 We live in the era of the Cloud, Kubernetes clusters, and geo-redundant data centers. But sometimes, the most critical infrastructure is much closer to the ground. Literally.
This story comes from a moment of pure realization. I was at the office while a colleague was working remotely. He called me up, looking a bit sheepish, and asked for a favor: &ldquo;Can you reboot the tower under my desk? There was a power cut and it didn&rsquo;t come back up.&rdquo;
I was confused. Why did he need his office desktop running if he was working from home?
I crawled under the desk, fought through the dust bunnies, and found the machine. Then I saw the sticky note: &ldquo;Production Server - DO NOT UNPLUG.&rdquo;
I froze. &ldquo;This&hellip; is production?&rdquo; I asked.
&ldquo;Yeah,&rdquo; he replied casually. &ldquo;It feeds data to the main app. It&rsquo;s been running like that for years.&rdquo;
It turns out our &ldquo;high-availability&rdquo; architecture had a single point of failure: a standard desktop PC, resting on the floor, vulnerable to the cleaning crew&rsquo;s vacuum cleaner and accidental kicks.
It’s a reminder that Shadow IT is real, and sometimes &ldquo;Enterprise-grade&rdquo; just means &ldquo;It hasn&rsquo;t crashed&hellip; yet.&rdquo; 😅

summary:
 It all started with a classic developer frustration:
&ldquo;Why doesn’t this app build the same way on my machine?!&rdquo;
A colleague leaned over, smiling with the confidence of someone who has already been converted:
&ldquo;You should just use Nix.&rdquo;
How complicated could it be?
Well&hellip; Nix isn’t just a package manager. It’s a whole paradigm shift: reproducibility, determinism, portability, system stability: everything defined declaratively. It promises environments that never drift and setups that behave exactly the same everywhere. And then there’s NixOS. Not just a tool, but an entire operating system built on the same ideas.

contents:
 It started as a simple mission: build a Kubernetes POC to explore the benefits and rethink the current architecture. The demo worked, the checklist was green, everyone was happy.
We made it clear to the client:
&ldquo;This is only a demo environment, nothing critical.&rdquo;
They nodded, satisfied. We moved on.
A few weeks later, the phone rang. It was the same client. Except this time, they didn’t sound calm at all. 😨
&ldquo;Everything’s gone! Our production is down!&rdquo;
An incident at the OVH datacenter had taken out their entire infrastructure. Servers, backups, everything hosted in the same place. A total loss.
For a moment, silence. Then came the question we didn’t expect:
&ldquo;Can we use the Kubernetes POC as production?&rdquo;
The POC was running, tests were green, and the app didn’t need long-term persistence hopefully. Their business processed streaming data for the day or week, not years. So we took a breath and said: &ldquo;Let’s go.&rdquo;
The next few hours were chaos. Scaling up replicas, securing ingress, adding monitoring, cleaning up demo secrets, turning our quick prototype into something that could actually handle real traffic.
And somehow, against all odds, it held. The client’s app came back online.
A few hours later, the same person called again. This time, they were smiling.
&ldquo;It works perfectly!&rdquo;
We smiled too. Then quietly thought:
&ldquo;It was never supposed to&hellip;&rdquo; 😅
